                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d137">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94 Conference/138: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-10-30T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 30, 1937—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>276. Your 503, October 30, 4 p.m. Inasmuch as news reports and <hi rend="italic"
                        >ballons d’essais</hi> concerning Japanese attitude may be frequent in the
                    coming days and as the Department desires to have as authoritative information
                    as practicable, the Department desires that you use your discretion as to making
                    informal inquiries of the Government in regard to any such reports, including
                    the report under reference. With <pb facs="0134" n="126" xml:id="pg_126"/>
                    further reference to the latter report, the Department would suggest that you
                    make no special and separate approach but take occasion to make inquiry in
                    regard thereto when you are approaching the Foreign Office on some other
                    matter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
